04242nam a22004455i 9780773564589DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19941994xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735645897 a10.1515/97807735645892doi  a(DE-B1597)655087  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aLE3.D32 ǂb W35 1994 vol. 1eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a378.716/2251 aWaite, P.B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLives of Dalhousie University, Volume 1 :b1818-1925, Lord Dalhousie's College /cP.B. Waite. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tA Brave Beginning 1816-1821 -- tNew Building, Silent Rooms 1821-1837 -- tOne College or Several? 1838-1847 -- tThrough the Shallows 1848-1864 -- tGreat Talent, Little Money 1863-1879 -- tGeorge Munro and the Big Change 1879-1887 -- tA Maturing Confidence 1887-1901 -- tExpanding : A Quest for Space 1901-1914 -- tThe Great War and After 1914-1922 -- tTowards University Federation 1921-1925 -- tAppendices -- tThe Dalhousie Act of 1863 -- tAgreement of Association between Dalhousic University and King’s College -- tEnrolment at Dalhousic, 1863-4 to 1914-5 -- tOrigins of Dalhousic Students -- tTwo Dalhousie Student Songs -- tBibliographic Essay -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFinanced by British spoils from eastern Maine in the War of 1812, modelled on the University of Edinburgh, and shaped by Scottish democratic education tradition, Dalhousie was unique among Nova Scotia colleges in being the only liberal, nonsectarian institution of higher learning. Except for a brief flicker of life (1838-43), for the first forty-five years no students or professors entered Dalhousie's halls a reflection in part of the intense religious loyalties embedded in Nova Scotian politics. The college building itself was at different times a cholera hospital and a Halifax community centre. Finally launched in 1863 and by 1890 embracing the disciplines of law and medicine, Dalhousie owed its driving force to the Presbyterians, retaining a double loyalty to their ethos of hard work and devotion to learning and to a board, staff, and student body of mixed denominations. P.B. Waite enlivens his descriptions of the life of the university with evocative portrayals of governors, professors, and students, as well as sketches of the social and economic development of Halifax. A welcome addition to the histories of Canadian universities, this volume and its forthcoming companion, dealing with the years 1925 to 1980, contribute significantly to our knowledge of the sometimes bitter internecine struggles that accompanied the development of higher education in Canada. "Everywhere is evident the deft turn of phrase, the captivating descriptions, the beautifully drawn word pictures that do much to enliven and illuminate the story . It possesses many strengths, including clarity and liveliness, and tells us much about Dalhousie as an institution of buildings, presidents, and professors." B. Moody, Department of History, Acadia University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356458940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773564589423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773564589/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles